I have found a way to add backticks to the column names in hibernate.

 1. Open the xml file (TableName.hbm.xml) relative to the pojo file which has been mapped.
 2. Find the property for the relative column.

        &lt;property name=&quot;key&quot; type=&quot;string&quot;&gt;
            &lt;column name=&quot;key&quot; /&gt;
        &lt;/property&gt;
 3. Surround the column name with square brackets.

        &lt;property name=&quot;key&quot; type=&quot;string&quot;&gt;
            &lt;column name=&quot;[key]&quot; /&gt;
        &lt;/property&gt;

----------

But this is a painstaking process as You&#39;ll have to do this to all the columns one by one for all the [MySQL keywords][1]. The best way is to avoid adding [MySQL keywords][1] as your database, table or column name.

References :

 - [How to use database reserved keyword in Hibernate ?](http://www.mkyong.com/hibernate/how-to-use-database-reserved-keyword-in-hibernate/)



  [1]: https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.5/en/keywords.html
